article.description: Lauren Jackson had 19 points and 13 rebounds to lead Seattle to a 75-67 victory at Houston in the opener of their first-round WNBA playoff series.
article.headline: Despite sore back, Jackson leads Storm to road victory
article.linkText: Despite sore back, Jackson posts double-double in Storm win
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- The Seattle Storm are just one win away from the
Western Conference Finals thanks to gutsy performances by Lauren
Jackson and Betty Lennox.

Nursing a sore back, Jackson had 19 points and 13 rebounds to
lead the Storm to a 75-67 victory over the Houston Comets in the
opener Tuesday night of their first-round WNBA playoff series.

Jackson made six of 13 shots and helped the defending champions
take a 1-0 lead back to Seattle for Thursday's Game 2 in the
best-of-three series.

After scoring just one point in the first half, Lennox finished
with 18 overall and added eight rebounds and four assists. Lennox
made four of her seven shots and nine of 10 free throws.

"I made the decision that I was going to play tonight," said
Jackson who injured her back in the regular-season finale against
Phoenix on Saturday. "This was huge for us. Going on the road and
winning is big, and we definitely want to win the series in two
games so we can relax and prepare for the next round."

Seattle, which lost both games at Houston during the regular
season, won just six of its 17 road games in 2005.

"I just started the game focused on defense," Lennox said.
"That is my job, and later in the game I just took what their
defense gave me.

"I know I have to go out there and stay calm, but I have to
play aggressive defense. That is what gets me going and it did
tonight."

Michelle Snow scored 15 of her 21 points in the second half to
give the Comets a 50-48 lead with 9:21 left. But the Storm used a
12-3 spurt to take control of the game and never trailed again.

Sheryl Swoopes added 15 points for the Comets.

"I think we have to find a better way of making something
happen when we can't score," Snow said. "And we've got to find a
way to make stops. You're going to have nights where you don't make
shots and you just have to be able to stop the other team. Tonight,
we didn't do that."

Seattle opened the game with a 23-10 surge as Jackson scored 10
of the team's first 17 points. But the Comets responded with a 9-2
spurt to get back in the game and trailed just 33-28 at halftime.

"We just had to rely so much on Lauren in the first half and
she really came up big for us," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said.
"You know she wasn't 100 percent, but sometimes when you're hurt
you are focused only on the game itself."

Thompson and Swoopes combined to make just six of 20 shots in
the opening half, but Dominique Canty made each of her four free
throws to help Houston stay close.

Reserve Tanisha Wright scored seven points for the Storm and was
5-for-5 from the free throw line.

"We've had some frustrating moments with this team and this was
just another tonight," Comets coach Van Chancellor said. "We just
could not get a shot to drop."
